1
00:00:00,875 --> 00:00:26,257
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa

2
00:00:26,812 --> 00:00:31,158
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:32,759 --> 00:00:43,473
So on this full moon, by the way, I hope you saw the blood moon for the full moon itself on the clear sky.

4
00:00:43,514 --> 00:00:48,399
It was it wasn't actually the full moon, but it was it was very red.

5
00:00:49,420 --> 00:00:50,662
Don't know whether you all caught that.

6
00:00:50,783 --> 00:00:51,603
It was very lovely.

7
00:00:54,503 --> 00:01:00,131
So the topic I've chosen for this one is dukkha and sila.

8
00:01:01,454 --> 00:01:06,221
So these are words that I'm sure you're familiar with, but it's good to have a little reminder.

9
00:01:07,664 --> 00:01:15,837
Dukkha, translated as unsatisfactoriness, as suffering, simply means hard to bear.

10
00:01:16,120 --> 00:01:19,222
But why does it manifest?

11
00:01:19,242 --> 00:01:32,055
So it manifests because of three basic roots, these unwholesome roots, the delusion, which forks off into some form of acquisitiveness and some form of aversion.

12
00:01:32,254 --> 00:01:37,278
And the aversion spikes off into hatred and fear.

13
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:45,807
So these are our basic attitudes that arise out of this deep delusion.

14
00:01:47,373 --> 00:02:03,239
So in order to go backwards to the original delusion, we have to work through the moral laws and ethical guidance.

15
00:02:04,120 --> 00:02:09,729
So the moral laws, I'm just using these words to mean two different things.

16
00:02:09,770 --> 00:02:12,655
The moral laws are basically things like, you know, not to kill.

17
00:02:13,056 --> 00:02:19,711
But the ethical guidance is really about relationships, about changing our relationship.

18
00:02:19,730 --> 00:02:26,766
And, you know, not only to people, animals, plants, but even to material things.

19
00:02:27,568 --> 00:02:33,039
So, for instance, at Heyeji Monastery, the founding monastery of Zen,

20
00:02:33,340 --> 00:02:41,491
I'm told that when they take water from a well, they will use the water, but always leave a little bit to put back into the well.

21
00:02:42,252 --> 00:02:43,313
It's a sort of offering.

22
00:02:43,375 --> 00:02:46,419
It's a sort of acknowledgement of the preciousness of water.

23
00:02:49,282 --> 00:02:52,987
Now, the thing about this suffering, remember, is that we cause it to ourselves.

24
00:02:53,088 --> 00:03:00,079
And what's difficult for us to really accept is that we actually are doing it since we were born.

25
00:03:00,359 --> 00:03:03,043
In fact, we're probably doing it in the womb.

26
00:03:03,597 --> 00:03:22,513
And you have to make this distinction between the pressures coming upon us, even as babies, which are usually not meant to be harmful, such as the process of birth, feeling hungry and mummy's not there.

27
00:03:22,532 --> 00:03:27,997
And of course, there are acts against us which can be harmful.

28
00:03:28,859 --> 00:03:32,641
But whatever happens to us

29
00:03:32,992 --> 00:03:53,905
is shall we say the original pain how we react to it through aversion etc is our suffering and you have to we have to recognize that if that were not so it would be impossible to become fully liberated unless we got rid of the

30
00:03:54,272 --> 00:04:14,272
the actual cause of our suffering if we believe other people are the cause of our suffering then basically we've got to get rid of other people and then we can be liberated but it's the very fact that we cause our own suffering that we can become fully liberated from it

31
00:04:16,327 --> 00:04:26,384
Now, I just want to just remind you of things, but I really want to center upon what are known as the defilements and the latent tendencies.

32
00:04:26,564 --> 00:04:27,747
But we'll come to that in a minute.

33
00:04:27,767 --> 00:04:33,396
So the five basic laws are places that I'm sure none of us go there.

34
00:04:33,737 --> 00:04:39,788
But it's good to know that there is, you know, things that we don't do anymore, like kill people.

35
00:04:39,767 --> 00:04:42,211
We don't kill anybody if we can.

36
00:04:42,531 --> 00:04:43,494
And we don't steal.

37
00:04:43,613 --> 00:04:44,735
We don't tell lies.

38
00:04:46,237 --> 00:04:48,461
We don't abuse our sexual powers.

39
00:04:48,942 --> 00:04:57,435
The last one's a bit difficult, not to take drugs and drink and all that sort of stuff, which which make the mind fuzzy.

40
00:04:58,156 --> 00:05:03,425
We do live in an alcohol culture, but it's up to the individual.

41
00:05:03,646 --> 00:05:04,526
But I think.

42
00:05:04,507 --> 00:05:21,704
If one brings to mind that alcohol, no matter how little it is, is actual pure poison to the body, probably worse than any of the drugs, then that might go for non-alcoholic wine and beers, which I can tell you now are very good.

43
00:05:25,380 --> 00:05:34,730
So, uh, the one about telling, uh, what happens is of course, that when we take those precepts, uh, obviously we move towards the opposite.

44
00:05:35,250 --> 00:05:41,377
So we, we don't kill, uh, kill anybody, but kill any being or anything like that.

45
00:05:41,396 --> 00:05:44,620
And we, we, we just naturally move towards protecting them.

46
00:05:45,120 --> 00:05:47,423
It's just a natural movement towards that.

47
00:05:48,564 --> 00:05:51,507
Sometimes that first precept is, um,

48
00:05:52,312 --> 00:05:56,798
translated as no harm, but it's not, it's actually killing.

49
00:05:56,819 --> 00:06:01,064
So it's actually a refinement if you're not harming any living being.

50
00:06:03,487 --> 00:06:11,458
Not to steal, when we give that up, of course, we know that that leads to a harmonious society and eventually generosity.

51
00:06:12,519 --> 00:06:20,430
Sexual powers is, of course, the use of those is out of respect and within a loving relationship.

52
00:06:20,983 --> 00:06:28,137
And when it comes to lying, of course, right speech, it splits into four different types.

53
00:06:28,237 --> 00:06:30,903
I mean, there are great big whoppers that we don't want to tell anymore.

54
00:06:31,343 --> 00:06:33,487
But slandering is a bit more difficult.

55
00:06:33,528 --> 00:06:35,432
We will let words slip.

56
00:06:36,661 --> 00:06:56,997
find ourselves saying things about people um and then there's abusive language of clear of course and uh just wasted talk you know just talking for talking sake and what we're moving towards is kindly speech uh truthful beneficial and most uh of of of

57
00:06:57,367 --> 00:07:10,350
importance to speak, to say things at a suitable time, because often we're saying what we want to say, but it's not quite the right time to say it.

58
00:07:12,233 --> 00:07:13,536
And we have this other

59
00:07:14,089 --> 00:07:20,444
category of hindrances where all these things come up as hindrances to our meditation when we're sitting.

60
00:07:21,004 --> 00:07:29,483
So it's just another sort of list which allows us to see where these defilements within us

61
00:07:29,918 --> 00:07:31,500
and how to deal with them.

62
00:07:31,521 --> 00:07:33,644
Each category has a way of dealing with them.

63
00:07:33,704 --> 00:07:34,706
I'm sure you remember.

64
00:07:35,146 --> 00:07:41,598
So the first one being all to do with sensual desires, avarice, greed, and all that sort of stuff.

65
00:07:41,759 --> 00:07:45,386
The next one is all the hatreds, the grudges, the vendettas.

66
00:07:46,767 --> 00:07:48,430
And then the...

67
00:07:51,776 --> 00:07:54,541
I've just moved a bit, just a minute.

68
00:07:54,843 --> 00:08:07,922
Yeah, and then there's this sloth and torpor, which is, you know, it comes about through our habit of using sleep to escape, to get rid of ourselves for a little while.

69
00:08:07,942 --> 00:08:10,084
I think somebody called it the duvet dive.

70
00:08:10,545 --> 00:08:16,434
So when you do that, of course, you're developing an energy which is pulling you down.

71
00:08:16,473 --> 00:08:18,276
It's like a whirlpool, you know.

72
00:08:18,956 --> 00:08:24,444
So these things have to be overcome, have to be allowed to drain themselves.

73
00:08:25,149 --> 00:08:32,400
And then there's that whole area of restlessness caused by just inner turbulence.

74
00:08:32,942 --> 00:08:44,239
But that also contains guilt, remorse and shame, which are secondary effects of doing something harmful.

75
00:08:45,534 --> 00:08:52,565
And then finally, skeptical doubt, which is quite a problem if you have it badly because you can't make a decision.

76
00:08:53,046 --> 00:08:57,392
You keep sort of making lists for and against.

77
00:08:58,712 --> 00:09:02,839
If you have a relationship where you might, yes, you are attracted.

78
00:09:02,918 --> 00:09:03,440
Could it work?

79
00:09:03,480 --> 00:09:04,221
Could it not work?

80
00:09:04,301 --> 00:09:05,943
Before you know it, the person's left you.

81
00:09:06,543 --> 00:09:07,605
It's the same with a job.

82
00:09:08,086 --> 00:09:08,727
Shall I go for it?

83
00:09:08,748 --> 00:09:09,649
Shall I not go for it?

84
00:09:09,788 --> 00:09:10,529
And he's gone.

85
00:09:11,471 --> 00:09:17,643
So it often comes from fear of failure or a lack of self-esteem or something like that.

86
00:09:19,706 --> 00:09:24,976
Anyway, just moving on to the kilesa.

87
00:09:25,037 --> 00:09:28,783
So this is often translated as the 10 defilements.

88
00:09:28,864 --> 00:09:33,732
Now, in the early scriptures, the word kilesa is used as a sort of general term.

89
00:09:34,202 --> 00:10:02,067
way of pointing to that within us which is unwholesome but of course later on it's very the early scriptures can't resist and the Abidama couldn't resist in making lists so they've given us a list of ten of these defilements and none of them will come as a shock I mean you know they're there but

90
00:10:02,467 --> 00:10:08,698
The reason for looking at this is in order to for self-reflection.

91
00:10:08,719 --> 00:10:17,312
So that when we see thoughts coming up, when we see our actions coming up, then it sort of categorizes it and it gives us some idea of how to deal with it.

92
00:10:18,495 --> 00:10:25,927
So the first one, obviously, is to do with sensual desire, basic sensual desire, you know, the greed, the lust, the avarice and so on.

93
00:10:27,815 --> 00:10:29,717
The next one is to do with hate.

94
00:10:30,438 --> 00:10:33,985
So it's unforgivingness and things like that, you know, holding grudges.

95
00:10:35,706 --> 00:10:37,028
The next one is delusion.

96
00:10:37,629 --> 00:10:42,477
And this is always around this fundamental problem of identity.

97
00:10:42,778 --> 00:10:48,506
It's always about this feeling of being a self, a person, something that doesn't change within us.

98
00:10:49,177 --> 00:10:57,349
And this, of course, then gives us this moving from the self, which is actually only seeking happiness.

99
00:10:57,870 --> 00:10:58,910
It's only seeking happiness.

100
00:10:59,331 --> 00:11:03,076
Then it gives us some sort of purpose for life to seek this happiness.

101
00:11:03,476 --> 00:11:08,725
But unfortunately, as we know, human life doesn't eventually satisfy us.

102
00:11:08,884 --> 00:11:14,932
You know, it's not it's not somewhere where we are going to feel completely satisfied.

103
00:11:15,688 --> 00:11:18,552
And this also manifests as conceit.

104
00:11:19,094 --> 00:11:23,759
So conceit has three manifestations.

105
00:11:23,799 --> 00:11:29,327
Of course, the obvious one is, you know, I am better than, I'm better than you, et cetera.

106
00:11:30,328 --> 00:11:35,176
And then you get the opposite of, you know, I'm not as good as, right?

107
00:11:35,775 --> 00:11:40,582
And then you get a more subtle one where you sort of feel that this is okay.

108
00:11:40,763 --> 00:11:42,926
I'm equal to, I'm equal to this person.

109
00:11:42,946 --> 00:11:44,227
So there doesn't seem to be any,

110
00:11:44,207 --> 00:12:10,822
conceit of I'm better or worse you know that seems to be that seems to be a good place to be it's sort of wholesome but unfortunately you are creating a group of people who all think that they they are equal now once you've done that there are other groups which are not equal and they are actually worse or better or better so it's it's it's a subtle one that

111
00:12:13,299 --> 00:12:15,264
The next one is wrong views.

112
00:12:15,585 --> 00:12:19,514
And this really is this goes back again to the self.

113
00:12:20,275 --> 00:12:27,933
And it's about believing that something of our personhood is is eternal.

114
00:12:28,488 --> 00:12:36,260
I mean, we all know the body will die, but the heart-mind, the mental body continues to live, never changes.

115
00:12:37,101 --> 00:12:50,243
The soul, often people will talk about their souls as being this unchanging person, basically, but without a physical body.

116
00:12:50,729 --> 00:12:53,251
And that, of course, is not the Buddha's teaching.

117
00:12:53,312 --> 00:12:59,441
The subtle body, the body that seeks rebirth is just as impermanent as this one.

118
00:12:59,780 --> 00:13:04,687
It is just another, it's just a more finer energy.

119
00:13:05,107 --> 00:13:17,445
Now, when I say that, you know, sometimes you can experience that, you know, when you're there with an emotion, something loud, like you might be feeling irritated or

120
00:13:17,880 --> 00:13:22,956
or anxious is a bit difficult, irritation, yeah, or anger, that's a good one.

121
00:13:23,477 --> 00:13:28,092
And you're in the body and you can feel it, you can feel it.

122
00:13:29,517 --> 00:13:32,024
You might be able, you know,

123
00:13:32,241 --> 00:13:40,231
by centering in on it very clearly, by holding your attention right there, it might just separate for you.

124
00:13:40,611 --> 00:13:49,864
And then you'll see that the mind's anger isn't that bad, but that when it touches the physical base of the body, it's like a sounding box.

125
00:13:49,923 --> 00:13:53,067
It comes back as very loud, as very burning.

126
00:13:53,807 --> 00:14:03,342
And little experiences like that prove to the meditator that these two things, the body and mind, are actually two different forms of energy.

127
00:14:03,884 --> 00:14:06,427
But neither of them are permanent.

128
00:14:06,827 --> 00:14:08,431
They're arising and passing away.

129
00:14:08,471 --> 00:14:14,119
And the opposite of eternalism, of course, is annihilationism.

130
00:14:15,321 --> 00:14:19,587
Like the idea that when you die, well, you're dead and that's it.

131
00:14:19,727 --> 00:14:21,029
So you should be happy with that.

132
00:14:21,567 --> 00:14:25,131
Now, in the Buddhist time, there were materialists.

133
00:14:25,272 --> 00:14:30,880
They were people who believed that there wasn't a soul, there wasn't anything.

134
00:14:30,941 --> 00:14:35,407
It was, you know, you were just this body and that when you died, you died.

135
00:14:35,488 --> 00:14:41,196
So these days we would have scientific materialists who would take that position.

136
00:14:42,390 --> 00:14:46,236
And definitely the Buddha was against both, right?

137
00:14:46,618 --> 00:14:55,552
And he tended to be accused of being an annihilationist, not an eternalist, because of his teaching of not-self.

138
00:14:56,373 --> 00:14:59,017
And it became very confusing, this not-self business.

139
00:14:59,577 --> 00:15:09,394
And the James said, we believe, ourselves and the Brahmins and the Brahmins, we believe that there is an eternal soul.

140
00:15:09,897 --> 00:15:12,779
And the materialists believe that there isn't.

141
00:15:13,341 --> 00:15:19,048
But the Buddhists haven't made their mind up.

142
00:15:20,269 --> 00:15:25,054
That was how confused people were with this doctrine of not-self.

143
00:15:25,916 --> 00:15:28,960
And there are occasions in the scriptures which are quite funny, actually.

144
00:15:29,581 --> 00:15:32,823
We'll do that some other time.

145
00:15:32,844 --> 00:15:35,888
Then we've got this skeptical doubt, which we've talked about.

146
00:15:36,568 --> 00:15:39,211
And torpor, again, which we've talked about.

147
00:15:39,562 --> 00:15:40,563
and restlessness.

148
00:15:41,184 --> 00:15:43,908
So those are your 10 kilesa.

149
00:15:44,308 --> 00:15:52,921
Sensual desire, hatred, delusion, conceit, wrong view, skeptical doubt, torpor, and restlessness.

150
00:15:53,421 --> 00:15:57,245
What I'm going to do is just put these lists onto a PDF if you want to have a look.

151
00:15:58,006 --> 00:16:06,177
But there's lots of stuff on the websites if you want to go into a bit more deeply.

152
00:16:06,832 --> 00:16:16,109
But the next bit is particularly interesting, I think, for us as Westerners, is this idea of anusaya, which are latent tendencies.

153
00:16:16,490 --> 00:16:22,740
So this tells you that within us there are these habits, sankara.

154
00:16:22,760 --> 00:16:29,432
So sankara is often translated as volitional conditioning, which is really confusing.

155
00:16:29,799 --> 00:16:39,461
But if we think about habits, it's just what we habitually do, all that, the way we think, the way we speak, our thought patterns.

156
00:16:39,761 --> 00:16:41,264
These are all habits.

157
00:16:41,546 --> 00:16:46,336
And the compendium of habits is what we would call our personality, character.

158
00:16:47,538 --> 00:16:47,860
Now,

159
00:16:48,328 --> 00:16:53,735
it's understood that these are lying underneath everything we're doing.

160
00:16:54,317 --> 00:17:04,590
And given an opportunity, given some sort of catalyst, some sort of stimulus, there will arise out of this sankara a response.

161
00:17:05,151 --> 00:17:09,797
So, for instance, all of us have some amount of anger within us.

162
00:17:10,178 --> 00:17:15,003
And if somebody stands on your foot, then that's a little stimulus.

163
00:17:15,305 --> 00:17:17,728
And this anger will want to sort of reply to it.

164
00:17:18,366 --> 00:17:20,409
And it's lying there dormant.

165
00:17:20,869 --> 00:17:21,130
Okay.

166
00:17:21,150 --> 00:17:22,311
It's lying there dormant.

167
00:17:23,053 --> 00:17:34,026
And, and what the Buddha is saying is that these are actually underneath our obvious consciousness, but that they're always, they're always ready.

168
00:17:34,125 --> 00:17:37,430
And they're always in many ways affecting the present moment.

169
00:17:38,391 --> 00:17:45,599
So, um, the, you, it's translated as bent bias, proclivity, all those sorts of words.

170
00:17:46,480 --> 00:17:47,142
And, um,

171
00:17:49,551 --> 00:17:51,976
They're exactly the same.

172
00:17:52,057 --> 00:18:05,320
The list is much the same as the defilements, of course, with one extra one or one different one, which is the tendency of the desire to become.

173
00:18:05,740 --> 00:18:10,529
In other words, that will to live and its opposite, the will not to live.

174
00:18:10,914 --> 00:18:22,105
So this will to live will lead us to beliefs of eternalism and the desire not to live will lead us to beliefs about annihilationism.

175
00:18:22,846 --> 00:18:32,875
And obviously, if you have that desire to live, then you'll do everything to keep alive and you will substantiate your life.

176
00:18:32,895 --> 00:18:38,121
You'll try to make it safer and safer with more money, more friends, et cetera, et cetera.

177
00:18:38,141 --> 00:18:40,163
It causes us to be acquisitive.

178
00:18:40,513 --> 00:18:59,772
If you are on the other side, where there's a sort of feeling of okay with annihilation, with the fact that death is the end of it and all that, then you'll find often, you'll find such people often taking refuge in sleep, the duvet dive.

179
00:18:59,792 --> 00:19:05,038
As soon as something's too much, well, you just lie down and go to sleep.

180
00:19:06,058 --> 00:19:10,182
But of course, on its worst level, it's suicide.

181
00:19:10,567 --> 00:19:12,230
just wanting to get rid of yourself.

182
00:19:12,990 --> 00:19:15,834
Unfortunately, in Buddhist understanding, that doesn't work.

183
00:19:16,173 --> 00:19:17,214
It will re-arise.

184
00:19:18,435 --> 00:19:22,140
So it's not a good solution.

185
00:19:24,241 --> 00:19:33,791
So that tendency there is put in as an underlying tendency, which is making us grasp everything which proves to us that we're alive.

186
00:19:34,393 --> 00:19:39,157
And that means trying to make ourselves happy, defending what...

187
00:19:39,526 --> 00:19:41,888
makes ourselves happy from any enemies.

188
00:19:42,209 --> 00:19:43,390
So there's your aversion.

189
00:19:43,810 --> 00:19:46,634
And if the enemy is too big, well, you run for it.

190
00:19:47,154 --> 00:19:55,904
So we're constantly trying to manipulate our lives in order to establish this constant state of living happily.

191
00:19:57,445 --> 00:20:08,419
Now, the last thing that I just want to mention is, of course, that it's translated as tendencies.

192
00:20:09,022 --> 00:20:13,067
So obviously these days we're very much aware of our prejudices.

193
00:20:13,628 --> 00:20:15,750
And there are two words that people are using.

194
00:20:15,790 --> 00:20:23,621
They use, I mean, the commentators, they use the word prejudice, which is a hard sort of word.

195
00:20:23,661 --> 00:20:25,663
There's almost an activity there.

196
00:20:26,263 --> 00:20:35,335
You know, if you're racially prejudiced or sexually prejudiced and somebody calls you that, there's a sort of feeling of you being actively so.

197
00:20:35,702 --> 00:20:42,576
So the other word that is being used is bias, which is slightly softer on a person.

198
00:20:42,596 --> 00:20:57,423
But I think that if we use these two words in the sense of the defilements and the latent tendencies, then it allows us to accept that all these things,

199
00:20:57,978 --> 00:21:19,277
prejudices are within us it's part of the baggage that we get when we are born into a culture and there's i've got a list here of well-known prejudices so there's racism obviously and tribalism which is a sore lesser form sexism ageism i'm very much against that

200
00:21:20,017 --> 00:21:29,011
classism, homophobia, nationalism, religious prejudice, and xenophobia.

201
00:21:29,172 --> 00:21:30,453
And that's only a short list.

202
00:21:31,576 --> 00:21:33,479
There's lots and lots of other prejudices.

203
00:21:34,540 --> 00:21:38,686
So it's being kind to ourselves.

204
00:21:38,767 --> 00:21:43,715
It's recognizing that we will have these prejudices within us.

205
00:21:44,376 --> 00:21:44,656
Now,

206
00:21:45,346 --> 00:21:50,287
and they can manifest and sometimes it can be embarrassing for us.

207
00:21:51,130 --> 00:21:53,922
But how do we overcome

208
00:21:54,491 --> 00:21:55,613
these prejudices.

209
00:21:55,633 --> 00:21:59,998
Well, obviously, on the obvious side, you don't indulge them.

210
00:22:00,278 --> 00:22:20,819
But the other thing that the Buddha often talks about is this yoniso manasikara, this sort of wise attention, this being really awake, that in any situation, you are aware of unwholesome thoughts as they arise, not after they've arisen and done something, but as they arise.

211
00:22:21,104 --> 00:22:29,834
And when we are awake enough to actually catch these little unwholesome thoughts coming up, they very quickly dissipate.

212
00:22:30,335 --> 00:22:44,451
And in that way, these prejudices, these biases begin to be exhausted of their energy and they lose that power to take us by surprise.

213
00:22:47,233 --> 00:22:47,954
Now,

214
00:22:48,728 --> 00:22:56,818
I think one of the difficulties is that it's very difficult for us to say to ourselves, well, I am racially prejudiced.

215
00:22:57,480 --> 00:23:03,086
Well, to say that and to mean it as an active thing, of course, wouldn't be correct.

216
00:23:03,667 --> 00:23:08,694
But to say that there is in me that still, that sankara, that conditioning.

217
00:23:09,619 --> 00:23:19,452
and to be aware should it ever arise and not to indulge it, I think that's a more truthful way of being with these conditionings within us.

218
00:23:20,193 --> 00:23:30,727
And it's also, I think, how should we say, comforting to know that every person in the world will have these prejudices, right?

219
00:23:30,747 --> 00:23:36,555
It doesn't matter what ethnic group you come from, what race you belong to, whatever,

220
00:23:37,311 --> 00:23:45,747
These are just basic prejudices that are completely universal, doesn't matter where you live.

221
00:23:47,950 --> 00:23:53,019
So that allows us, I think, to be more open about ourselves, at least to ourselves anyway.

222
00:23:53,740 --> 00:24:00,833
And that means that we will be aware of these things when they arise and they don't sneak out as Freudian slips, right?

223
00:24:00,853 --> 00:24:02,796
Which can be very embarrassing.

224
00:24:05,981 --> 00:24:19,013
So what we've done this evening is just revise these moral precepts and begun to look at much more of this idea of relationship.

225
00:24:19,453 --> 00:24:21,355
And we've looked at the more negative side.

226
00:24:22,257 --> 00:24:26,941
At another time, we'll be looking at the more positive side, the virtues.

227
00:24:26,961 --> 00:24:33,626
But it's just ways in which we can reflect upon these things during the

228
00:24:33,808 --> 00:24:42,119
you know, whenever the occasion arises and allows us to find a way to heal the heart of these things.

229
00:24:43,741 --> 00:24:47,247
So that's the purpose of, you know, bringing these things to mind.

230
00:24:47,827 --> 00:24:59,923
And as I say, if you want to go deeper into it, there's lots of stuff on the websites, lots of talks to Dharma Seed and things like that.

231
00:24:59,943 --> 00:25:00,525
Very good.

232
00:25:01,348 --> 00:25:02,550
I think I've done my bit there.

233
00:25:02,590 --> 00:25:18,682
So I hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused confusion, and that you will, by your constant effort, release yourselves from all suffering and achieve the peace of Nibbana.

